Motive

Why this topic?


  • Cancer is a leading cause of death worldwide
    • 1,000,000 new diagnosed
    • Over 600,000 deaths
  • Data is convenient to obtain and analyze

Background

What is cancer?

  • Cancer is a group of diseases characterized with abnormal growth of cells

Background Cont.

How to study cancer?

  • Measure gene expression
    • A gene is a fragment of DNA that expresses a cellular function

Data Cont.

The Cancer Genome Atlas (TCGA)


We downloaded gene expression of 32 human tissues

Samples
  • Tumor and "normal" tissues
  • Number of samples vary
  • Not all tissues have normal samples

Objective

  1. Identify difference of expression in selected genes between normal and tumor tissues using visualizations
  2. Identify difference of expression in all genes between normal and tumor tissues using paired t-test

Literature Review

Two of the main type of genes that play a role in cancer

  • Tumor suppressors: Normal genes that slow down cell division, repair DNA mistakes, or tell cells when to die
    • BRCA1
    • BRCA2
    • TP53
  • Oncogenes: If a gene that is responsible for cell to grow become permanently activated when it is not supposed to be.
    • KRAS
    • MYC
    • ABL1



Gene Location on Chromosomes

Results

Heat Maps

  • Most Common way to visualize Gene Expression Data
  • Shiny App: https://ajvanderwal.shinyapps.io/ShinyApp/
    • Each column represents a Gene (BRCA1, BRCA2, TP53, KRAS, MYC, and ABL1)
    • Each row represents a sample
    • Red indicates high gene expression, green indicates low gene expression
  • High Gene Expression does not indicate tumor

Results Cont.

Heat Maps

  • Overexpression of the MYC gene in most of the tissues analyzed
    • CESC, KICH, TGCT are the tissues with an exception and have low expression
  • No expression in normal nor tumor across all tissues for BRCA1 & BRCA2
    • Slight Expression of BRCA1 in TGCT
  • 40% of the tissues show a high expression of TP53
  • Similarly, 43% of the tissues have a high expression of ABL1
  • ABL1 and KRAS are more expressed in tumor tissues

Results Cont.

Boxplots

  • Allows viewer to visualize the distribution of each gene's expressiveness
  • Tumor samples have higher expression and more spread

Results Cont.

Paired t-Test

  • Goal is to see which tissues have a statistically significant difference between tumor and normal gene expression
  • Averaged all samples' expression for all 60,483 genes
  • Conducted t-test using all 60,483 genes of a tissue
  • Difference between tumor gene expression average and normal gene expression average

Results Cont.

Paired t-Test

  • Goal is to see which tissues have a statistically significant difference between tumor and normal gene expression
  • Averaged all samples' expression for all 60,483 genes
  • Conducted t-test using all 60,483 genes of a tissue
  • Difference between tumor gene expression average and normal gene expression average

Paired t-Test

t-Test is uses each gene (60,483) as the samples and uses the tumor average and normal average as the values

This is done throughout cancer research

Gene Tumor Average Normal Average
ENSG00000242268 983.6 101.8
ENSG00000244268 70.1 643.2
ENSG00000457068 8749.5 983.2
… …
ENSG00000952268 102934.3 2022.3

Summary

  • Downloaded and analyzed samples from TCGA (32 tissues)
  • Visualized gene expression of 6 genes related to cancer (heat maps and boxplots)
  • Performed paired t-test to find significant difference between normal and tumor tissue samples

Future Directions

  • Obtain more normal tissue samples
  • Visualized gene expression of 6 genes related to cancer (heat maps and boxplots)
  • Analyze more data by capturing other features (mutation rate, copy number, fusion, etc.)
  • Statistically analyze individual genes
  • Use other techniques to analyze genes (non-parametric statistics, ML clustering algorithms, etc.)
